        "id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2006_Solutions_2006s_page_006_14",
        "observed_type": "list_item",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "B-6 First solution: We start with some easy upper and lower bounds on an. We write O(f(n)) and S(f(n)) for functions g(n) such that f(n)/g(n) and g(n) / f(n), respectively, are bounded above. Since an is a nondecreasing sequence, an+1 - An is bounded above, so An = O(n). That means an - 1/k = S(n-1/k), so",
